<<<api>>>: StringTokenizer.nextToken
<<<code>>>: 
```java
String line = "34 55 64";
StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(line);
int x = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
int y = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
int z = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
```
<<<explanation>>>: In this code, we first create a StringTokenizer object 'st' with the string 'line'. The StringTokenizer class in Java is used to break a string into tokens. The nextToken() method of StringTokenizer class is used to return the next token from the StringTokenizer object. We then use the Integer.parseInt() method to convert these tokens (which are strings) into integers. This way, the numbers in the string are stored in the integer variables x, y, and z.
